b'[<p><i><b>UFC 18: The Road to the Heavyweight Title</b></i> was a <a href="/wiki/Mixed_martial_arts" title="Mixed martial arts">mixed martial arts</a> event held by the <a href="/wiki/Ultimate_Fighting_Championship" title="Ultimate Fighting Championship">Ultimate Fighting Championship</a> on January 8, 1999 in <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/New_Orleans,_Louisiana" title="New Orleans, Louisiana">New Orleans, Louisiana</a>.  The event was seen live on pay per view in the <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">United States</a>, and later released on <a href="/wiki/Home_video" title="Home video">home video</a>.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-1"><a href="#cite_note-1">[1]</a></sup><sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-2"><a href="#cite_note-2">[2]</a></sup>\n</p>, <p>The event featured a UFC Lightweight Championship (now known as the Welterweight Championship) bout and six other bouts. UFC 18 was technically part two of what the UFC called "The Road To The Heavyweight Title", a tournament, spanning four events, held to crown the new UFC Heavyweight Champion after the title was vacated by <a href="/wiki/Randy_Couture" title="Randy Couture">Randy Couture</a> (due to contract disputes).  \n</p>, <p>Part one was held at <a href="/wiki/UFC_Brazil" title="UFC Brazil">UFC Brazil</a>, with <a href="/wiki/Tsuyoshi_Kosaka" title="Tsuyoshi Kosaka">Tsuyoshi Kosaka</a> taking a win to advance to UFC 18. UFC 18 featured the first US appearance of MMA legend <a href="/wiki/Bas_Rutten" title="Bas Rutten">Bas Rutten</a>, and the first appearance of the late <a href="/wiki/Evan_Tanner" title="Evan Tanner">Evan Tanner</a>, who would go on to become the UFC Middleweight Champion.\n</p>, <p>UFC 18 marked the first card where the initials "UFC" replaced "The Ultimate Fighting Championship" in the logo and when mentioned by the announcers/commentators. The new logo used the similar character from the old logo (with hands on his hips instead of punching the globe) combined with the letters UFC on the bottom.\n</p>]'